    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1954-06-14T19:55:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1954-06-14T19:55:00-05:00" n="746"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d746">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">396.1 GE/6–1454: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Secretary of State</gloss> to the
                            <gloss type="to">United States Delegation</gloss>
                    </hi>
                    <note n="1" xml:id="d746fn1">Drafted by <persName corresp="#p_TWR1"
                            >Tyler</persName> of <gloss target="#t_EUR1">EUR</gloss>/<gloss
                            target="#t_WE1">WE</gloss>. Repeated to Paris as telegram 4580 and to
                        Saigon as telegram 2601.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <seg rendition="#left">
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">top secret</hi>
                    </seg>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1954-06-14T20:55:00-04:00"
                            >June 14, 1954—8:55 p.m.</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <gloss target="#t_Tedul1">Tedul</gloss> 198. It seems clear that apart from
                    official French-Viet Minh military talks, there are parallel conversations going
                    on both between individuals from each side (<gloss target="#t_Dulte1"
                        >Dulte</gloss> 173<note n="2" xml:id="d746fn2">Dated June 12, <ref
                            target="#pg_1126">p. 1126</ref>.</note>), and other probably important
                    talks mentioned <gloss target="#t_Dulte1">Dulte</gloss> 179<note n="3"
                        xml:id="d746fn3">Dated June 14, <ref target="#pg_1132">p. 1132</ref>.</note>
                    which, in spite fact they are called “underground military talks”, may have
                    considerable substantive political significance.</p>
                <p>We would not wish be in position where this subterranean negotiation between
                    French and Viet Minh might have result our being suddenly faced with terms
                    proposed settlement which we would not feel able accept and from which we might
                    have to dissociate ourselves.</p>
                <p>We therefore attach great importance to ascertaining scope and character current
                    Franco-Viet Minh talks other than official military discussions, and we would
                    like leave it to you find out by whatever means you consider appropriate as much
                    as possible about them. We would of course hope to be kept informed by French on
                    continuing basis.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_DJF1">
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Dulles</hi>
                        </persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
